# Accessibility & Inclusive Design

Target: **WCAG 2.2 Level AA**. Accessibility is not a feature ‚Äî it is a baseline quality attribute of every page and component.

## The POUR Principles

Every design decision must satisfy all four:

1. **Perceivable** ‚Äî information must be presentable in ways all users can perceive
2. **Operable** ‚Äî UI must be navigable and usable by all input methods
3. **Understandable** ‚Äî content and operation must be comprehensible
4. **Robust** ‚Äî content must work reliably across assistive technologies

## Semantic Structure

- Use HTML elements for their meaning, not their appearance: `<nav>`, `<main>`, `<section>`, `<article>`, `<aside>`, `<header>`, `<footer>`, `<button>`, `<a>`
- Every page must have exactly one `<main>` landmark
- Heading levels (`h1`‚Äì`h6`) must form a logical outline ‚Äî never skip levels for styling
- Lists of items use `<ul>`, `<ol>`, or `<dl>` ‚Äî not `<div>` chains
- Tables use `<th scope="col">` or `<th scope="row">` ‚Äî never layout tables
- Use `<button>` for actions, `<a>` for navigation ‚Äî never `<div onclick>`

## Color & Contrast

- **Text contrast:** minimum 4.5:1 for normal text, 3:1 for large text (‚â•18pt or ‚â•14pt bold)
- **Non-text contrast:** minimum 3:1 for UI components and graphical objects (borders, icons, focus indicators, chart elements)
- **Never use color alone** to convey meaning ‚Äî always pair with text, icon, pattern, or shape
- Test with simulated color blindness (protanopia, deuteranopia, tritanopia) ‚Äî if meaning is lost, add a redundant cue
- Ensure sufficient contrast in both light and dark contexts

## Keyboard Accessibility

- Every interactive element must be reachable and operable via keyboard
- Tab order must follow the visual reading order (avoid positive `tabindex` values)
- Focus must be visible at all times ‚Äî use `:focus-visible` with a 2px+ solid outline at ‚â•3:1 contrast against adjacent colors
- **Focus not obscured (WCAG 2.4.11):** focused elements must not be entirely hidden behind sticky headers, drawers, or overlays
- Provide keyboard shortcuts for frequent actions, disclosed via UI (e.g., `‚åòK` badge)
- Trap focus inside modals and dialogs; restore focus to the trigger on close
- Custom components must implement appropriate ARIA keyboard patterns (arrow keys for tabs, Escape to close, Enter/Space to activate)

## Touch & Pointer

- **Target size:** minimum 24√ó24 CSS pixels (WCAG 2.5.8); prefer 44√ó44 for primary actions
- **Spacing:** at least 8px between adjacent touch targets
- **Dragging alternatives (WCAG 2.5.7):** every drag-and-drop interaction must have a single-pointer alternative (buttons, menus, or form controls)
- Touch targets can be visually smaller if padding expands the tappable area

## Images & Media

- Every `<img>` must have an `alt` attribute ‚Äî descriptive for content images, empty (`alt=""`) for decorative ones
- Decorative images also get `aria-hidden="true"`
- Complex images (charts, diagrams) need a text summary or linked data table
- Videos need captions; audio needs transcripts
- Avoid autoplay for media with sound

## ARIA ‚Äî Use Sparingly

- Prefer native HTML semantics over ARIA ‚Äî ARIA is a repair tool, not a first choice
- If ARIA is necessary: `aria-label` for invisible labels, `aria-describedby` for supplemental descriptions, `aria-live` for dynamic content announcements, `aria-expanded`/`aria-controls` for disclosure widgets
- Never use `role` to override an element's native semantics unless building a true custom widget
- Test with a screen reader (VoiceOver, NVDA) ‚Äî if the experience is confusing, simplify the markup

## Motion & Animation

- Respect `prefers-reduced-motion: reduce` ‚Äî disable or minimize non-essential animations
- Essential transitions (page loads, route changes) should complete quickly (<300ms)
- Never use flashing or strobing content (risks seizures)
- Parallax scrolling and auto-advancing carousels must have pause controls

## Cognitive Accessibility

- **Consistent help (WCAG 3.2.6):** help mechanisms (links, chat, FAQs) must appear in the same location on every page
- **Redundant entry (WCAG 3.3.7):** never ask users to re-enter information they already provided in a multi-step flow
- **Accessible authentication (WCAG 3.3.8):** avoid cognitive function tests (CAPTCHAs); allow password managers and copy-paste
- Use plain language, short sentences, and clear labels
- Provide visible instructions before complex interactions

## Testing Checklist

Before considering a page complete, verify:

- [ ] Keyboard-only navigation reaches and operates all interactive elements
- [ ] Focus order matches visual order
- [ ] All images have appropriate alt text
- [ ] Color contrast passes (text ‚â•4.5:1, non-text ‚â•3:1)
- [ ] No information conveyed by color alone
- [ ] Heading hierarchy is logical
- [ ] ARIA attributes are valid and necessary
- [ ] Page works at 200% zoom without horizontal scrolling
- [ ] Touch targets meet minimum size (24√ó24 CSS px)
